@alexander-akait Thanks for your suggestion, but in my real project, there are many modules duplicately bundled in the way described in the OP. Applying the suggestion results in so many small chunks, one for each of the duplicate modules, which seems unnecessary to me.

I think it's natural to bundle the duplicate modules only into the entrypoint chunks when the modules are imported by modules of both entrypoint chunks and async chunks, as webpack has already achieved this in most of the cases (For example in the OP, webpack wouldn't duplicately bundle module `src/moduleAB.js` into `dist/featureA.js`, whereas `dist/featureA.js` imports `src/moduleAB.js`. I take it that webpack knows `src/moduleAB.js` is already available in the entrypoint chunk `dist/entryA.js`, so it's unnecessary to bundle `src/moduleAB.js` again into `dist/featureA.js`)

