To fix the issue of having duplicate copies of the same file in different directories, you can modify the webpack configuration to use a single shared folder for the dependencies. One way to achieve this is by using the resolve.alias option in the webpack configuration file to map the dependency path to a single shared folder. For example:
`resolve: {
  alias: {
    'vue': path.resolve(__dirname, 'libs/node_modules/vue/dist/vue.runtime.esm.js')
  }
}`
This configuration will ensure that all references to the vue dependency will be resolved to the same location, thus avoiding having multiple copies of the same file in different directories. You can apply a similar configuration for other dependencies as needed.

