After look into this issue in depth. 

I found the issue is caused by `HarmonyDetectionParserPlugin` + `innerGraph`. And it cannot be successfully run in both webpack@4 and webpack@5 that is not the [above issue mentioned](https://github.com/webpack/webpack/issues/14307)  that it's a bug introduced by webpack@5.

First, for `HarmonyDetectionParserPlugin`. JsParser will skip walking the arguments of `"define" and "exports"` callExpression.
https://github.com/webpack/webpack/blob/964c0315df0ee86a2b4edfdf621afa19db140d4f/lib/dependencies/HarmonyDetectionParserPlugin.js#L104

So we need move variableDeclaration to `top-level`, like

```js
// lib.js
export default 42;

// index.js
import foo from './lib.js';
const bar = require('./lib.js');

const arg = function (require) {
  console.log(foo); // not work
  console.log(bar); // ok
}

define(arg);

noop(function () {
  console.log(foo); // ok
  console.log(bar); // ok
});

function noop() {}
```

So the above code can be successfully bundled and run in webpack@4, but not in webpack@5 which supports `innerGraph`.

innerGraph analyze `top-level-symbol` and infer the usage of all symbols. 

For above code, `arg` is a `top-level-symbol`, and `foo`.usedExport will be set to true. when `arg` is used.

Unfortunately, `HarmonyDetectionParserPlugin` don't allow to walk `arg` Identifier because of `define`.

Finally dep(foo).usedExport will be set to false which makes 2 module can't be connected. 

We can temporarily workaround it by setting `optimization.innerGraph: false`. 

```
// webpack.config.js
module.exports = {
	// ...
	optimization:{
		// ...
		innerGraph: false
	}
}
```

