@KeerthiSwarna08 Those configuration changes are just workarounds the core problem is that the behaviour changed in 0.59.0 and webpack is not behaving as documented. To quote the docs:
> Calls to import() are treated as split points, meaning the requested module and its children are split out into a separate chunk.

https://webpack.js.org/api/module-methods/#import-1

I would say that this is a bugfix and the behavior was incorrect before, the main problem with webpack is that it always generates a JS file, which leads to the generation of extra JS code and extra chunks, this problem has existed for a long time, as you can see it is even in the bug tracker - https://github.com/webpack/webpack/issues/11671 and more.

In short, when the entry point is not a JS file, we do not generate JS code and extra chunks now, this allows you to use webpack as a regular tool for working with assets, CSS and other non-JS resources and has less runtime JS code.

How to fix this?

Write JS code to request an asset:

**loader.js**

```js
const { resolve } = require("path");
const { callbackify } = require("util");

module.exports = function loader(source) {
  const data = JSON.parse(source);

  callbackify(async () => {
    data.asset = await this.importModule(`!!./js-loader.js!${resolve(this.context, data.asset)}` );

    return JSON.stringify(data);
  })(this.async());
};
```

**js-loader.js**

```js
module.exports = function loader() {
  return `module.exports = require(${JSON.stringify(this.utils.contextify(this.context, this.remainingRequest))});`
}; 
```

After this, webpack will understand that it needs to generate execution code for JS and return URL. 

When you simply submit an asset, webpack simply generates a binary file of the asset and that's it.

