Do you want reuse `lib.js` somewhere? I.e. Do you want allow people consume it like npm package or do you want to use it in only your app? If you want to share your library like a package, you need to use `output.library` (using multi compiler mode, i.e. multiple configuration)/`entry.library` and webpack will generate only required code, I recommend to use it like an entrypoint and set `library: 'module'` - https://webpack.js.org/concepts/entry-points/#entrydescription-object, other entries (which are for application should use `dependOn`).

Shorty:

```js
module.exports = {
  entry: {
    pageOne: { import: './page-one.js', dependOn: 'lib' },
    pageTwo: { import: './page-two.js', dependOn: 'lib' },

    lib: {
      library: 'module',
      import: './lib.js',
    },
  },
};
```

Also don't forget you need to exclude `lib` chunk from splitting - https://webpack.js.org/plugins/split-chunks-plugin/#splitchunkschunks, you can split it and it will work, but I don't think other developers import splitted chunk before library usage.

