Yes, that is expected, because you have:
```
if(typeof exports === 'object' && typeof module === 'object')
		module.exports = factory(require("antd"), require("md5"), require("react"));
```

in `os-common/dist/index.js` webpack tries to resolve these `require`s and because you have `node_modules` with these packages in `os-common` webpack resolves them, in real world example `umd` library usually don't have `node_modules` and so webpack doesn't resolve different `react` version.

To fix it you can:
- use the `alias` option https://webpack.js.org/configuration/resolve/#resolvealias (you can list more of them)

```js
resolve: {
  alias: {
    react: require.resolve('react'),
  }
}
```

Alternative solution:

```js
resolve: {
  modules: [path.resolve(__dirname, './node_modules'), '...'],
}
```

It says webpack try to resolve dependency in my `./node_modules` and then in other `node_modules`s, but be careful here, because some dependencies can have the packages with lower/higher versions than you have and it can break code in such packages (and so in you application).

- Using monorepo approach and using `npm link`, your `react` and not only deps should be hoisted to the top of your project and be the only ones. 

That is how resolution works in Node.js, webpack do nothing specially here.

