@alexander-akait I've tracked down my issue it's the change from:

`if (!directories.has(filename) && !currentAssets.has(filename)) {
  diff.add(filename);
}`

to 
`if (
	!hasFile(directories, filename) &&
	!hasFile(currentAssets, filename)
) {
	diff.add(filename);
}`

hasFile is a new function that calls "normalize" on each path pair before comparing. This is vastly slower than the native O(1) Map.has and Set.has functions and accounts for all the extra time. 

I suggest reverting back to .has(), and pre-normalizing the paths if really needed.

There are two cases for handling unreachable or unused statements:
1. unreachable or unused if/else statements\
Eliminating entire statements, as minifiers (i.e. terser) do, may not always be worthwhile. Retaining `else { /* removed by dead control flow */ }` is working fine in `Firefox` without warning.

2. unreachable or unused code followed by dead control flow
